<HEADLINE>
<P>
STEADY AS SHE GOES, ON COURSE TO DISASTER?; 
</P>
<P>
LACKING A COMPASS, BUSH TEAM MAY TOO EASILY ACCEPT A TILT TO LEFT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM BETHELL, Tom Bethell is the Washington editor of the American Spectator. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The Establishment is back," a Washington Post editor wrote a few days ago, 
"not just the individuals and the pedigrees but the state of mind." David 
Ignatius, the editor of Outlook, noted that Secretary of State-designate James 
A. Baker III was busily consulting with his predecessors in a way that was 
reminiscent of "the best and the brightest" at the outset of John F. Kennedy's 
Administration. Andover, Yale and Princeton are back in the saddle. The new 
buzzwords in President Bush's Washington are said to be bipartisan foreign 
policy and partnership with Congress. 
</P>
<P>
How long is this chumminess likely to last? Lurking beneath the comparison with 
the best and the brightest is the implicit prediction of disaster ahead. 
Kennedy's Ivy Leaguers soon strolled into the quagmire of Vietnam. Does a 
similar fate await Bush's team, so many of whom come from a comparable 
background? 
</P>
<P>
Conservatives fear that this might be the case. Bush clearly regards 
conservatives as one among many interest groups to be placated, not as the 
source of a philosophy that is perilous to ignore. By all accounts, policy in 
the Bush Administration is to be determined by a pragmatic weighing of 
conflicting advice. This sounds fine, but in practice it doesn't work. 
</P>
<P>
In the absence of a philosophy of government it is difficult to assess the 
merits of advice given by conflicting experts. President Jimmy Carter stayed up 
till midnight in the Oval Office agonizing over rival reports on energy policy. 
To deregulate or not to deregulate? Meanwhile, we waited in gasoline lines. 
Armed with a philosophy, President Ronald Reagan decided right away, and by 
mid-afternoon could usually head off to the family quarters upstairs. This is 
not to say that a free-market philosophy (Reagan's, in the case of energy 
policy) is always right, but some philosophy is needed when decisions have to 
be made every day, and often quickly. 
</P>
<P>
It is not clear at present that Bush has such a philosophy. The public service 
that his patrician father urged on him merely restates the problem of 
government. It does not solve it. Washington is currently celebrating the 
belief that the new skipper has arrived at the White House without a compass. 
This is a pleasant prospect for Beltway hands, who have a compass of their own 
and will be only too happy to let Bush use it. It comes with a built-in 
Democratic "tilt," and suggests a course to the left of center. 
</P>
<P>
It is considered tactless to point out that the present consensus in Washington 
was achieved by the Reagan Administration's latter-day adoption of Democratic 
policies. Somehow in the last two years Reagan mislaid his compass and borrowed 
the Beltway's model. Bush has strongly signaled that he intends to continue 
using it. 
</P>
<P>
Conservatives believe that this course -- steady as she goes -- will end in one 
disaster or another. And they note the irony: Reagan's capitulations came late 
enough in the day that their effects would not be experienced on his watch, but 
on that of his successor. 
</P>
<P>
The principal architects of Reagan's emerging pragmatism, it is widely believed 
in Washington, were Secretary of State George P. Shultz and James Baker. Now, 
as the incoming secretary of state, Baker will justly inherit the whirlwind. 
Here are a few of the storm warnings. 
</P>
<P>
A new agreement in Southern Africa, signed after the November election, could 
easily lead to the Marxist takeover of Namibia and its permanent enthronement 
in Angola. 
</P>
<P>
In Nicaragua the Contras have been abandoned in all but name. Cubans and 
Soviets will now have a freer hand to continue their surreptitious military 
advance in that country, from which tens of thousands of Nicaraguans are 
fleeing to the United States. Bush has suggested that he will "take a look at" 
our refugee policy, and has hinted at the worst solution: more federal aid for 
refugees. 
</P>
<P>
El Salvador's economy has been reduced to shambles by U.S. economic aid, and 
its government is propped up by U.S. military aid. Nothing has been done to 
address the Latin American debt problem, the "Baker plan" having failed. Only a 
move toward free markets will help Brazil, Mexico, Argentina and Peru. Yet 
bailing out U.S. banks as a prelude to further loans, which appears to be 
Baker's strategy, is the one course of action guaranteed to postpone the shift 
to free markets. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, all these countries are threatened by leftward-moving governments. 
But the real danger lies in the Soviet Union, precisely because their economy 
appears to be collapsing. No longer can the Soviets believe that they will 
overtake us by peaceful means. Militarily they are still strong, but this 
cannot long outlast economic decline. 
</P>
<P>
Prudently, we should calculate that their military commanders may soon start 
thinking what is for us the unthinkable: Use it or lose it. And so we should be 
thinking of defense -- strategic defense. But the Establishment, the one that 
is now "back" and running things in Washington, does not want to defend 
America. And it does not want to because it is afraid to. "This tremendous 
opposition to introducing a defensive element to the U.S. deterrent strategy," 
Air Force Chief of Staff Larry D. Welch said recently, "has to be one of the 
most mysterious pieces of political chemistry we've seen." Meanwhile, James 
Baker wants to continue pursuing arms control. In this connection, arms-control 
director Gen. William F. Burns told me recently that the nearly completed START 
agreement will entail dismantling half of our existing nuclear submarines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012089-0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 7712 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 20, 1989, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 7; Column 1; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
714 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIZING UP PRESIDENT BUSH: EFFECTIVE, NOT A DAREDEVIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RAYMOND PRICE, Raymond Price writes a syndicated column in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush will not be a clone of President Reagan. But how different will 
he be, and in what ways? 
</P>
<P>
The short answer to the first question is very, and to the second, most. Not 
different in the basic objectives that he seeks, but different in the ways in 
which he pursues them. 
</P>
<P>
Ronald Reagan touched a certain mystic chord in the nation's heart. A Bush 
presidency will be more prose and less poetry. Reagan kept his eye on the goal. 
Bush will focus more on the means of reaching it. Reagan had an unparalleled 
ability to reach out and touch millions of Americans at once through 
television. Bush will reach out and touch many more people individually, and 
will track more closely the inner workings of his own Administration. 
</P>
<P>
George Bush has always had an adventurous spirit, but has followed it in a 
measured way. In World War II he became the Navy's youngest pilot, and a good 
one -- he won the Distinguished Flying Cross and three Air Medals -- but being 
a good combat pilot means being effective, not being a daredevil. After college 
he set out on his own for the oil fields of Texas, but carefully kept his ties 
to the banking world of the Northeast. He doesn't shrink from risks, but he 
prefers prudent risks. 
</P>
<P>
One of the strongest influences on his life was his father, U.S. Sen. Prescott 
Bush, who was also a managing partner of the elite New York investment-banking 
firm of Brown Brothers Harriman &amp; Co. 
</P>
<P>
As a senator Pres Bush didn't make large waves. That wasn't his style. But he 
did win high respect from his Senate colleagues. He had a firm sense of right 
and wrong, and held himself to rigorous standards of personal conduct. An 
ardent internationalist, he helped persuade Dwight Eisenhower to get into the 
1952 presidential race. He was courteous, sometimes even courtly, with a 
conservative's instinctive distrust of government panaceas but also a firm 
belief that government exists to serve the public, not vice versa. 
</P>
<P>
Call it social conscience or a patrician sense of noblesse oblige, but the 
whole Bush family was imbued with a deeply rooted sense of public duty. To the 
Bush clan, public service is not someone else's responsibility. It's theirs. 
</P>
<P>
George Bush is not a theoretician. He does not have an intellectual turn of 
mind. He habitually deals with the concrete, not the abstract. He does have a 
keenly honed sense of how the world works. As U.S. ambassador to the United 
Nations, head of the U.S. mission to China and director of the CIA, he saw the 
real world beyond the U.S. borders. And there is a down-home quality about his 
thought processes that creates real empathy with people on an individual basis 
while leaving his view of the bad guys and how they operate in the world 
remarkably unclouded. 
</P>
<P>
Because of this down-home quality and his own familiarity with Washington, the 
snake-oil salesmen who so heavily populate the Beltway area won't find him to 
be an easy sell. He has heard their pitches before. He knows the words -- and 
also the music. 
</P>
<P>
It's no coincidence that for years his closest political confidant and 
collaborator has been Secretary of State-designate James A. Baker III. Baker is 
called a pragmatist. To the rigid ideologue a pragmatist is a person without 
principle. In the real world a pragmatist is often one who maneuvers to get as 
much of what his principles dictate as he can, then moves on to the next 
battle. Ideologues make better copy because they make livelier drama. But 
mixing in some pragmatism makes better policy. 
</P>
<P>
Soon, of course, the "inconsistencies" game will begin. Analysts not capable of 
holding two thoughts in their heads at the same time will point to separate 
Bush initiatives and declare them inconsistent with one another. Already the 
game has begun. To 90% of the Beltway crowd, kinder and gentler means one 
thing: fatter federal social programs funded by higher taxes. Bush doesn't 
believe that taxes are necessarily kind and gentle. 
</P>
<P>
But if people read his lips correctly, the new President should not be a font 
of major surprises. By and large, he is the sort who says what he means and 
means what he says and who doesn't feel that he has to raise his voice to make 
his point. By listening more closely, those who at first find his actions 
puzzling may in time find them less so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
