<HEADLINE>
<P>
EXPLAINING THE REASON FOR ADJUVANT THERAPY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: The papers have been carrying stories about how women with breast 
cancer should have adjuvant therapy. Will you please explain what this is. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: You are probably referring to a National Cancer Institute Clinical 
Alert, which suggested that systemic adjuvant therapy may be beneficial if it 
is begun within six weeks of removal of a breast cancer. Adjuvant refers to 
treatment given in addition to the primary treatment. In the case of breast 
cancer, surgery is the primary treatment; adjuvant therapy may consist of 
radiation, chemotherapy or hormones. 
</P>
<P>
In general, physicians have used systemic adjuvant therapy in breast cancer 
patients whose lymph nodes contained cancer cells at the time they underwent 
surgery. Women whose breast cancer had not spread to lymph nodes generally did 
not receive systemic adjuvant therapy. 
</P>
<P>
I would advise any of my readers who may be concerned about these stories to 
discuss their feelings with their physician. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
