<P>
RODRIGUEZ STATUS REMAINS UNCLEAR FOR FULLERTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBYN NORWOOD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Cal State Fullerton gymnastics season opens tonight without a decision on 
whether men's team captain Eli Rodriguez will be permitted to compete while he 
awaits trial on a misdemeanor charge of aggravated assault. 
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez was suspended after his involvement in the stabbing of a former 
teammate in September. 
</P>
<P>
Coach Dick Wolfe, citing a shortage of available gymnasts, says it will be 
mathematically impossible for Fullerton to win without Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
"We don't have enough people to field five gymnasts in each event without him," 
Wolfe said. "We would have to take 0's, and you can't win if you do that." 
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez was allowed to resume practicing with the team in November after the 
charge was reduced from a felony to a misdemeanor. 
</P>
<P>
But Athletic Director Ed Carroll said the matter is "still under review" and 
that he didn't know if he would make a decision before the meet. 
</P>
<P>
"There's not a definite timetable," he said. 
</P>
<P>
The men take on San Jose State and the women take on Stanford. ROBYN NORWOOD 
</P>
</TEXT>
